icek]]\n* [[Connie Hawkins]]\n* [[Elvin Hayes]]\n* [[Spencer Haywood]]\n* [[Catfish Hunter]]\n* [[Dan Issel]]\n* [[Reggie Jackson]]\n* [[Jairzinho]]\n* [[Alberto Juantorena]]\n* [[Kevin Keegan]]\n* [[Mario Kempes]]\n* [[Billie Jean King]]\n* [[Guy Lafleur]]\n* [[Jack Lambert]]\n* [[Niki Lauda]]\n* [[Rod Laver]]\n* [[Pete Maravich]]\n* [[Roland Matthes]]\n* [[Bob McAdoo]]\n* [[John McEnroe]]\n* [[Pietro Mennea]]\n* [[Earl Monroe]]\n* [[Joe Morgan]]\n* [[Edwin Moses]]\n* [[Gerd Muller]]\n* [[Calvin Murphy]]\n* [[John Naber]]\n* [[Johan Neeskens]]\n* [[Jack Nicklaus]]\n* [[Tom Okker]]\n* [[Bobby Orr]]\n* [[Jim Palmer]]\n* [[Bernie Parent]]\n* [[Walter Payton]] \n* [[Tony Perez]]\n* [[Richard Petty]]\n* [[Willis Reed]]\n* [[Rivellino]]\n* [[Oscar Robertson]]\n* [[Larry Robinson]]\n* [[Pete Rose]]\n* [[Ken Rosewall]]\n* [[Nolan Ryan]]\n* [[Mike Schmidt]]\n* [[Tom Seaver]]\n* [[O. J. Simpson]]\n* [[Stan Smith]]\n* [[Mark Spitz]]\n* [[Ken Stabler]]\n* [[John Stallworth]]\n* [[Willie Stargell]]\n* [[Roger Staubach]]\n* [[Lynn Swann]]\n* [[Nate Thurmond]]\n* [[Wes Unseld]]\n* [[Guillermo Vilas]]\n* [[Bill Walton]]\n* [[Jerry West]]\n* [[Paul Westphal]]\n* [[Jo Jo White]]\n* [[Jamaal Wilkes]]\n* [[Lenny Wilkens]]\n* [[Mac Wilkins]]\n* [[Carl Yastrzemski]]\n* [[Dino Zoff]]\n* [[Zico]]\n{{div col end}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1970s in music]]\n* [[1970s in fashion]]\n* [[1970s in television]]\n* [[List of years in literature#1970s|1970s in literature]]\n\n===Timeline===\nThe following articles contain brief timelines which list the most prominent events of the decade:\n\n[[1970]] \u2022 [[1971]] \u2022 [[1972]] \u2022 [[1973]] \u2022 [[1974]] \u2022 [[1975]] \u2022 [[1976]] \u2022 [[1977]] \u2022 [[1978]] \u2022 [[1979]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Borstelmann, Thomas. ''The 1970s: A New Global History From Civil Rights to Economic Inequality'' (Princeton University Press; 2012) 401 pages; looks at new right movements, and the global impact of economic deregulation. [https://www.amazon.com/The-1970s-Economic-Inequality-ebook/dp/B005KLQYKE/ excerpt];  also [http://www.h-net.msu.edu/reviews/showrev.php?id=43066 online review]\n* Ferguson, Niall,  and Charles S. Maier, eds. ''The Shock of the Global: The 1970s in Perspective'' (2011) essays by leading scholars; 448 pp\n* La Barca, Giuseppe. ''International Trade in the 1970s: The U.S., the EC, and the Growing Pressure of Protectionism'' (London: Bloomsbury, 2013) 224 pp.\n* Padva, Gilad. Sexing the Past: Communal Exposure and Self-Examination in ''Gay Sex in the 70s''. In Padva, Gilad, ''Queer Nostalgia in Cinema and Pop Culture'', pp.&nbsp;58\u201371 (Palgrave Macmillan, 2014, {{ISBN|978-1-137-26633-0}}).\n* Wheen, Francis. ''Strange Days Indeed: The 1970s: The Golden Days of Paranoia'' (2010) 352pp; looks at general irrationalism (such as UFOs, psychic phenomena, mad cults), and terror (IRA bombings; Black September massacre at the Munich Olympics; Baader-Meinhof Gang in Germany; Symbionese Liberation Army.)\n\n===United States===\n* Berkowitz, Edward D. ''Something Happened: A Political and Cultural Overview of the Seventies'' (Columbia University Press, 2006). 283 pp., liberal perspective\n* Carroll, Peter.  ''It Seemed Like Nothing Happened: The Tragedy and Promise of America in the 1970s'' (1982)\n* Cowie, Jefferson R. ''Stayin' Alive: The 1970s and the Last Days of the Working Class'' (2010) [https://www.amazon.com/Stayin-Alive-1970s-Working-Class/dp/1565848756/ excerpt], on U.S.\n* Frum, David.  ''How We Got Here: The 70s'' (2000), conservative perspective [https://www.amazon.com/How-We-Got-Here-ebook/dp/B0047CQ31M/ excerpt and text search]\n* Kalman, Laura. ''Right Star Rising: A New Politics, 1974\u20131980'' (2010) 473pp; [https://www.amazon.com/Right-Star-Rising-Politics-1974-1980/dp/0393076385/ excerpt and text search]\n*Lehman, Katherine J.  '' Those Girls: Single Women in Sixties and Seventies Popular Culture'' (University Press of Kansas, 2011).  280 pp. [https://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=37968 online review]\n*  Sandbrook, Dominic. ''Mad as Hell: The Crisis of the 1970s and the Rise of the Populist Right'' (2012) [https://www.amazon.com/Mad-Hell-Crisis-1970s-Populist/dp/1400077249/  excerpt and text search]\n* Schulman, Bruce.  ''The Seventies: The Great Shift in American Culture, Society, and Politics'' (2001) [https://www.amazon.com/The-Seventies-American-Culture-Politics/dp/030681126X/ excerpt and text search]\n* Stein, Judith. ''Pivotal Decade: How the United States Traded Factories for Finance in the Seventies'' (2010) 384pp [https://www.amazon.com/Pivotal-Decade-Factories-Finance-Seventies/dp/030011818X/ excerpt and text search]\n\n===Britain===\n* Beckett, Andy. ''When the Lights Went Out: Britain in the Seventies'' (2009) 576pp [https://www.amazon.com/When-Lights-Went-Out-Seventies/dp/057122136X/ excerpt and textsearch]\n* Booker, Christopher. ''The Seventies: The Decade That Changed the Future'' (1980)\n* Sandbrook,  Dominic. ''State of Emergency: The Way We Were: Britain 1970\u20131974'' (2010) \n* Sandbrook,  Dominic.  ''Mad As Hell: The Crisis of the 1970s and the Rise of the Populist Right'' (2011) \n* Sandbrook,  Dominic.  ''Seasons in the Sun: The Battle for Britain, 1974\u20131979'' (2012)\n* Turner, Alwyn W. ''Crisis? What Crisis?: Britain in the 1970s'' (2009) 336pp [https://www.amazon.com/Crisis-What-Britain-1970s/dp/1845134257/ excerpt and text search]\n* Wybrow, Robert J. ''Britain Speaks Out, 1937\u201387: A social history as seen through the Gallup data'' (1989)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|1970s}}\n* [http://www.life.com/image/first/in-gallery/56251/heroes-of-the-1970s#index/0 Heroes of the 1970s] \u2013 slideshow by ''[[Life magazine]]''\n* [http://www.ultimate70s.com www.ultimate70s.com] \u2013 Day-by-day news, sports, weather, prime-time TV listings and more!\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n{{20th century}}\n\n[[Category:1970s| ]]\n[[Category:20th century]]\n", "name_user": "Mr. Brain", "label": "safe", "comment": "Jean-Louis Trintignant's name was in the wrong place.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1970s"}
{"title_page": "Nintendo Direct", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| italic_title             = yes\n| show_name                = Nintendo Direct\n| image                    = Nintendo Direct logo.svg\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = The main ''Nintendo Direct'' logo\n| native_name              = {{Infobox name module|Japanese|\u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc\u30c0\u30a4\u30ec\u30af\u30c8}}\n| genre                    = [[Presentation]]\n| creator                  = [[Satoru Iwata]]\n| developer                = [[Nintendo]]\n| presenter                = '''Various, presently:'''{{Video game release|WW|[[Yoshiaki Koizumi]] <small>(2017\u2013present)</small>|WW|[[Shinya Takahashi]] <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>|NA|[[Doug Bowser]] <small>(2019\u2013present)</small>}}{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;|title=Previous presenters|{{Video game release|WW|[[Satoru Iwata]] <small>(2011\u20132015)</small>|NA|[[Reggie Fils-Aim\u00e9]] <small>(2011\u20132018)</small>|NA|[[Bill Trinen]] <small>(2012\u20132016)</small>|EU|Satoru Shibata <small>(2012\u20132016)</small>|EU|Ed Valiente <small>(2015\u20132016)</small>|KOR|Hiroyuki Fukuda <small>(2012\u20132015)</small>|AU|Tom Enoki <small>(2014)</small>}}}}\n| narrated                 = \n| country                  = {{Unbulleted list|Japan|North America|Europe|Australia|South Korea}}\n| language                 = {{Unbulleted list|Japanese|English|Korean}}\n| executive_producer       = {{Unbulleted list|Satoru Iwata {{Small|(2011\u20132015)}}|[[Tatsumi Kimishima]] {{Small|(2015\u20132018)}}|[[Shuntaro Furukawa]] {{Small|(2018\u2013present)}} }}\n| camera                   = Single-camera\n| runtime                  = {{Nowrap|5\u201350 minutes}}\n| network                  = {{Unbulleted list|[[YouTube]]|[[Niconico]]||[[Twitch (service)|Twitch]]|[[Ustream]] {{Small|(discontinued)}}}}\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2011|10|21}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = [[Nintendo Power]]\n[[Nintendo Space World]]\n[[Nintendo Week]]\n| website                  = http://www.nintendo.com/nintendo-direct\n}}\n\n'''Nintendo Direct'''{{efn|{{Nihongo||\u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc\u30c0\u30a4\u30ec\u30af\u30c8|Nintend\u014d Dairekuto|lead=yes}}}} is an online presentation or live shows produced by [[Nintendo]], where information regarding the company's content or franchises is presented, such as information about games and consoles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/corporate/direct_links/index.html|title=\u4f1a\u793e\u60c5\u5831\uff1aNintendo Direct \u30ea\u30f3\u30af\u96c6|website=Nintendo of Japan|accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref> The presentations began in Japan and North America with the first edition on October 21, 2011, before later expanding to Europe, Australia, and South Korea.\n\n== Format ==\nNintendo Direct presentations vary in format between different presentations and regions.\n\n=== Regional differences ===\nNintendo Directs generally come in both regional and international formats.\n\n==== International ====\nFor subjects of a general worldwide appeal, a single Nintendo Direct is often localised for a simultaneous international broadcast. Usually, these will be recorded in Japanese, and presented by a Japanese presenter. Prior to Nintendo president Satoru Iwata's death, he would host Directs in both English and Japanese, with other languages' presentations being subtitled.\n\nUpon Iwata's death, Nintendo Directs did not receive a worldwide host until 2017, when Yoshiaki Koizumi from [[Nintendo EPD]] took over this role. Since 2018, Koizumi has shared this responsibility with Shinya Takahashi.\n\nSince 2017, the Japanese presenter and any narrators' roles will be dubbed or subtitled for international release, including into English.\n\nPresentations scheduled for around the time of the [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] are usually produced by [[Nintendo of America]], presented and narrated in English for international broadcast.\n\n==== Japan ====\nIn Japan, Nintendo Directs were most commonly presented by Nintendo's global president [[Satoru Iwata]] until his death in 2015, with [[Yoshiaki Koizumi]] now serving as host.\n\nSince 2017, Japan has hosted region-specific \"Indie World\" presentations, focusing on [[Indie game]]s published for Nintendo Switch.\n\nDirects focused on Super Smash Bros. are typically hosted by series creator [[Masahiro Sakurai]].\n\n==== North America ====\nIn North America, the videos were often presented by [[Nintendo of America]] president, [[Reggie Fils-Aim\u00e9]], and [[Bill Trinen]].\n\nFor international Directs produced in Japan since 2017, Nintendo of America will air a dubbed version of the Direct in English. Both the presenter and narrator will be dubbed by separate narrators.\n\nSince 2017, Nintendo of America has hosted presentations focusing on [[Indie game]]s published for Nintendo Switch. Between 2017 and 2019, these were branded as \"Nindies Showcase\", before aligning their branding to the Japanese \"Indie World\" banner.\n\n==== Europe and Australia ====\nEuropean Directs were presented by former [[Nintendo of Europe]] president, Satoru Shibata. These presentations were also broadcast in Australia.\n\nAustralia generally only airs the European output, but one Direct was created specifically for the region, broadcast on September 24, 2014. This Direct was hosted by Tom Enoki.\n\nFor international Directs produced in Japan since 2017, Nintendo of Europe airs the original Japanese audio for the presenters, but will use an English dub for the narrated sections. These are then subtitled for broadcast in other languages.\n\nSince 2017, Nintendo of Europe has broadcast presentations focussing on indie games published for Nintendo Switch. From 2017 to 2018, Nintendo of Europe broadcast the American \"Nindies Showcase\" presentations. In 2018 and 2019, Nintendo of Europe hosted its own \"Indie Highlights\" videos. From 2019, they returned to broadcasting Nintendo of America's presentations, now under the \"Indie World\" banner.\n\n==== South Korea ====\nSouth Korea has also aired exclusive Nintendo Directs hosted by Nintendo of Korea president, Hiroyuki Fukuda.\n\n==== Hong Kong and Taiwan ====\nA few Nintendo Direct presentations have been produced specifically for Hong Kong and Taiwan.\n\n=== Types of Nintendo Direct presentations ===\nOutside of the general Nintendo Direct presentations, which cover a range of titles, there are also Directs centred around specific titles or series. These are usually presented by the producer or director of the game or series, or employ a narrator.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+List of Nintendo Direct presentation types\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Type\n! scope=\"col\" | Logo\n! scope=\"col\" | Duration\n! scope=\"col\" | Content\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Nintendo Direct\n|[[File:Nintendo Direct logo.svg|alt=Nintendo Direct Presentation logo|center|140x140px]]\n| 25\u201350 minutes\n| The main type of Nintendo Direct presentation. Showcases information about software and hardware across all Nintendo platforms.\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Nintendo Direct Mini\n|[[File:Nintendo Direct mini logo.svg|alt=Nintendo Direct Mini presentation logo|center|140x140px]]\n| 5\u201315 minutes\n| A shorter version of the main type of Nintendo Direct. Also showcases information about software and hardware across all Nintendo platforms.\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Nintendo Direct special\n|Each Direct of this type has its own logo.\n| 5\u201350 minutes\n| A presentation that covers specific software titles, both from Nintendo and third-party developers. Usually hosted by the game's producer or makes use of a narrator.\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Indie World\n|[[File:IndieWorldLogo.jpeg|center|140px|alt=Indie World presentation logo]]\n| 17\u201328 minutes\n| A presentation focusing on [[indie game|titles by independent developers]] coming to Nintendo Switch. This specific presentation type was originally only shown in Japan but later added North America, and Europe.\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Nintendo E3 Presentations/Directs\n|Each Direct of this type has its own logo.\n| 20\u201345 minutes\n| A presentation on upcoming first/third party games that airs live during [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3]]. The presentation covers games that will release sometime between E3 to the end of the calendar year.\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |Discontinued Nintendo Direct presentation types\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Nintendo Direct Micro\n|[[File:Nintendo Direct Micro Logo.png|center|140px|alt=Nintendo Direct Micro presentation logo]]\n| 17 minutes\n| A one-off presentation that covered software and hardware across all Nintendo platforms. This type of Nintendo Direct has been discontinued. and was replaced by Nintendo Direct Mini\t\n\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Nintendo 3DS Direct\n|[[File:Nintendo 3DS Direct logo.png|center|140px|alt=3DS Direct Presentation logo]]\n| 30\u201350 minutes\n| A Nintendo Direct specifically concerning software and hardware related to the Nintendo 3DS family of consoles. This type of Nintendo Direct has been discontinued, although Nintendo 3DS games appear outside of this type.\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Wii U Direct\n|[[File:Nintendo Direct Wii U edition logo.png|center|140px|alt=Wii U Direct presentation logo]]\n| 30\u201350 minutes\n| A Nintendo Direct specifically concerning software and hardware related to the Wii U console. This type of Nintendo Direct has been discontinued following the end of Wii U production to make way for the Nintendo Switch.\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Nindies Showcase\n|[[File:Nindies Showcase logo.png|center|140px|alt=Nindies Showcase presentation logo]]\n| 10\u201330 minutes\n| A presentation focusing on [[indie game|titles by independent developers]] coming to Nintendo Switch. This specific presentation type was only shown in North America and Europe. This type of Nintendo Direct was replaced by \"Indie World\".\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Indie Highlights\n|[[File:IndieHighlightsLogo.jpeg|center|120px|alt=Indie Highlights presentation logo]]\n| 17\u201323 minutes\n| A presentation focusing on [[indie game|titles by independent developers]] coming to Nintendo Switch. This specific presentation type was only shown in Europe. This type of Nintendo Direct was replaced by \"Indie World\".\n|}\n\n==== Nintendo E3 Directs ====\nSince June 2013, in lieu of traditional large-scale [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] (E3) press conferences, Nintendo has opted to utilize the Nintendo Direct platform as an alternative method of conveying its news. Speaking at an annual March financial results briefing just two months prior, Nintendo CEO Satoru Iwata stated that the company\u2019s decision was determined by the fact that \u201cdifferent people demand different types of information\u201d, and that the Nintendo Direct platform had established itself to the point that Nintendo would \u201cbe able to deliver [their] messages more appropriately and effectively \u2026 based on the various needs of different groups of people\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/library/events/130425/04.html|title=Financial Results Briefing For Fiscal Year Ended March 2013|date=April 25, 2013|website=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> Christopher Dring of ''[[GamesIndustry.biz]]'' observed that the last press conference that Nintendo held at E3 in 2012 featured too much of a mix between Nintendo's new hardware for the [[Wii U]] and game announcements. Compared to other press conferences held that year, Nintendo's presentation left little for fans of the company to be excited for. By switching to Nintendo Directs, Dring opined that the company was able to better connect to fans using the Nintendo Direct presentations, made the faces of Nintendo's executives more visible, as well as having Directs outside of the E3 cycle to provide more frequent updates on game and hardware releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-01-12-nintendo-direct-has-transformed-the-companys-relationship-with-its-fans|title=Nintendo Direct has transformed the company's relationship with its fans|last=Dring|first=Christopher|date=January 12, 2018|work=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the stream of the prerecorded broadcast for E3 2013, Nintendo\u2019s website suffered from technical difficulties in the form of overloaded servers, rendering the live video unwatchable for many viewers, and prompting an official apology from Mr. Iwata.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Nintendo/posts/469863129764812|title=Nintendo - Hello everyone this is Satoru Iwata. Thank you\u2026|date=June 11, 2013|website=[[Facebook]]}}</ref> Despite these difficulties, Nintendo of America President Reggie Fils-Aim\u00e9 noted that secondary viewership following the initial broadcast still worked to popularize product promotion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/6/14/4429168/nintendos-e3-press-conference-absence-was-a-one-off-publisher-says|title=Nintendo's E3 press conference absence was a one-off, publisher says|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=September 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, in addition to the Direct, the company added \"Nintendo Treehouse: Live @ E3\" live streams to their presence at the trade event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2014/04/29/nintendo-reveals-its-e3-plans|title=Nintendo Reveals its E3 Plans Don't Include Live Conference|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=September 3, 2019}}</ref> Named after the Product Development department at Nintendo of America, these are daily streams from the show floor that feature NoA localization staff and game developers demoing and giving in-depth coverage of titles that were announced during that year's Direct. The year also began a trend of Nintendo hosting a game tournament sometime during the week, in which the participants compete in titles that had yet to be released.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+List of Nintendo E3 events\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Summary\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 2014\n|'''''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' Invitational'''\n| Sixteen professional ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' players invited to play ''[[Super Smash Bros. for Wii U]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/nqwnk-vFNpE7o0V1TrWTuiugb1JSq8g9|title=You're invited to the Super Smash Bros. Invitational at E3|date=May 20, 2014|website=Nintendo|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114202306/https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/nqwnk-vFNpE7o0V1TrWTuiugb1JSq8g9|archive-date=November 14, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F7UQU7Jzc04|title=Play Nintendo - Super Smash Bros. Invitational Highlights|date=June 12, 2014|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"rowspan=3\" | 2015\n|'''[[Nintendo World Championships 2015]]'''\n| Sixteen players, eight chosen from qualifying competitions throughout the United States and invited by Nintendo, compete in various Nintendo games, with the final game being ''[[Super Mario Maker]]''.<ref name=\"NWC2015 E3 Nintendo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/HNLBx_g_7fGRPfyY9JIRrCTTXrcpQ1ev|title=Nintendo World Championships headline Nintendo's expanded lineup at E3 2015|date=May 13, 2015|website=Nintendo|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705004750/http://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/HNLBx_g_7fGRPfyY9JIRrCTTXrcpQ1ev|archive-date=July 5, 2015|accessdate=June 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J9H8VcU21j4|title=Nintendo World Championships 2015|date=June 14, 2015|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 2016\n|{{N/A}}\n| Nintendo lacked both a tournament and a presentation this year, only having Nintendo Treehouse live streams that focused mainly on ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]'' and Nintendo 3DS games.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" | 2017\n|'''''[[Splatoon 2]]'' World Inkling Invitational'''\n| Professional ''[[Splatoon]]'' teams from the United States, Japan, Europe and Australia/New Zealand compete in a [[round-robin tournament]] with ''Splatoon 2'''s Turf War and Ranked Battle modes.<ref name=\"E32017 Nintendo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/nintendo-details-splatoon-2-and-arms-e3-tournaments|title=Nintendo details Splatoon 2 and ARMS E3 tournaments|date=June 1, 2017|website=Nintendo|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114202223/https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/nintendo-details-splatoon-2-and-arms-e3-tournaments|archive-date=November 14, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0jcfyDfv_bg&pbjreload=10|title=2017 Splatoon 2 World Inkling Invitational - Round Robin - Part 1 - Nintendo E3 2017|date=June 13, 2017|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''''[[Pokk\u00e9n Tournament DX]]'' Invitational'''\n| Four two-player teams consisting of [[YouTube]] and [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] personalities compete, with one member of each team using one of the new characters added for the game's Nintendo Switch release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/nintendo-adds-pokken-tournament-dx-to-the-e3-lineup|title=Nintendo adds Pokk\u00e9n Tournament DX to the E3 lineup|date=June 6, 2017|website=Nintendo|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114202109/https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/nintendo-adds-pokken-tournament-dx-to-the-e3-lineup|archive-date=November 14, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eFHrGNo-UEs|title=Pokk\u00e9n Tournament DX Invitational - Round 1 - Nintendo E3 2017|date=June 14, 2017|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''''[[Arms (video game)|Arms]]'' Open Invitational'''\n| Four E3 attendees compete against four professional fighting game players in a [[single elimination]] format with the various gameplay modes in ''Arms''.<ref name=\"E32017 Nintendo\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BTc5Ims9y3M|title=2017 ARMS Open Invitational - Round 1 - Nintendo E3 2017|date=June 14, 2017|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|'''''[[Splatoon 2]]'' World Championship Finals'''\n|Representatives from the United States, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Europe and Japan, will compete in a series of ranked matches for the grand prize at [[E3 2018]].\n|-\n|'''''Super Smash Bros.'' Invitational 2018'''\n|Professional ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' players and selected convention attendees at [[E3 2018]] got to play the upcoming ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'' title for the [[Nintendo Switch]].\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/E3/Nintendo-of-Europe-s-E3-2019-website-1557157.html|title=Nintendo of Europe: E3 2019|website=Nintendo of Europe|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|'''''[[Super Mario Maker 2]]'' Invitational 2019'''\n|Special guests invited by Nintendo get to play a wide variety of newly-made courses in the upcoming ''Super Mario Maker 2''.\n|-\n|'''''[[Splatoon 2]]'' World Championship 2019'''\n|Teams from North America, Europe, Australia/New Zealand and Japan, each the winners of their respective tournaments, will battle after a year of events to be given the world number one title.\n|-\n|'''''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'' World Championship 2019 3v3'''\n|Qualified teams of three from each of North America, Europe, Australia/New Zealand and Japan will compete against each other after each winning their regional tournaments.\n|}\n\n== List of presentations ==\nAlongside Nintendo Direct presentations, other Nintendo-produced online presentations without the \"Direct\" in its name are listed.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: 